1.  TYPE OF DATA                                                                
                                                                                
1.1  Parameter/Measurement.  Ozone concentration profiles of the                
stratosphere, as derived from solar occultation radiometric measurements.       
                                                                                
1.2  Unit of Measurement. 
                                                                                
         Parameter                   Unit                         
         ---------                   ----                       
         Ozone Number Density        1.0E11 cm**-3
         Ozone Volume Mixing Ratio       ----            
                                                                                
1.3  Data Source.  Parameters are derived from the Stratospheric Aerosol        
and Gas Experiment (SAGE I) instrument on the Applications Explorer             
Mission-2 (AEM-2) and the Stratospheric Aerosol and Gas Experiment              
(SAGE II) instrument on ERBS.  The 0.600 um channel, which is near the
center of the Chappuis ozone band, is the primary channel used for ozone
measurement.
                                                                                
1.4  Data Set Identification.  The Atmospheric Explorer Mission's 
SAGE I ozone data are identified within NCDS as SAGEI-PROF_OZONE.
The ERBS SAGE II ozone data are identified as SAGEII-PROF_OZONE.              
                                                                                
The data sets contain derived ozone number densities, volume mixing         
ratios, and corresponding error arrays for each sunrise and sunset event.       
Within NCDS, sunrise events are identified as 0 and sunset events are
identified as 1.
            
                                                                    
2.  SPATIAL CHARACTERISTICS                                                     
                                                                                
2.1  Spatial Coverage.  The orbital characteristics of SAGE I and SAGE II       
provide low- and mid-latitude coverage of ozone measurements.  Each         
instrument observes one sunrise and one sunset per orbit.  
                     
SAGE I:  There are 15 sunrise and 15 sunset events per day.  SAGE I         
events offer latitudinal sweep ranges of approximately 130 degrees within
a 4 week period.  In addition, they provide global coverage from 72        
degrees N to 72 degrees south during a year.  Successive observations of
the same type are separated by approximately 24 degrees longitude.           
                                                                                
SAGE II:  Spatial coverage is similar to that of SAGE I; however,        
coverage is provided from 80 degrees S to 80 degrees N annually.               
                                                                                
2.2  Spatial Resolution.  The spatial resolution of the SAGE I and SAGE II
data sets is the same.  The 1 micrometer wavelength measurement has a
vertical resolution of 1 km below 25 km and a resolution of 5 km above 25
km.  The vertical resolution of the 0.45 micrometer wavelength channel is 3
km below 25 km.  The horizontal resolution is about 250 km for all
wavelengths.   
                                                                                
                                                                                
3.  TEMPORAL CHARACTERISTICS                                                    
                                                                                
3.1  Temporal Coverage.  SAGE I data collection began February 21, 1979.
Four months after launch, a spacecraft power subsystem problem forced SAGE
I data collection to be limited to sunsets only (identified as "1" in
NCDS).  Limited operation continued until November 18, 1981.  SAGE II data
collection began October 5, 1984 and continues to the present time.         
                                                                                
3.2  Temporal Resolution.  Each satellite instrument makes two ozone 
profile determinations per orbit (96-97 minutes).  Each event is 
separated by approximately 24 degrees of longitude.  SAGE I and SAGE II 
each have 15 orbits per day.                                              
                                                                                
                                                                                
4.  INSTRUMENT DESCRIPTION                                                      

4.1  Mission Objectives.  The mission objectives of the SAGE I and SAGE
II are to determine the spatial distribution and map vertical profiles
of ozone.  Specific objectives are:

         a.  To develop a viable satellite-based remote sensing technique
             for measuring ozone.   

         b.  To utilize these measurements to study global circulation,
             transient stratospheric phenomena, and sources and sinks of
             individual species.

         c.  To investigate ozone optical properties using data from
             flight experiments and correlative observations.
            
4.2  Key Satellite Flight Parameters.  Nominal orbit parameters for SAGE I
and SAGE II are listed below:

                                 SAGE I                  SAGE II
                                 ------                  -------
     o  Launch Date         February 18, 1979       October 5, 1984
     o  Planned Duration    1 year                  1 year  
     o  Actual Duration     2 years and 9 months    Still operating
     o  Orbit               Non-sun synchronous     Non-sun synchronous
     o  Inclination         55 degrees              57 degrees
     o  Nodal Period        96.8 minutes            98 minutes

4.3  Principles of Operation.  SAGE I is a four-channel solar photometer 
with spectral bands at 0.385, 0.450, 0.600, and 1.00 micrometers.  SAGE II
is a seven-channel solar photometer with spectral bands 0.385, 0.448,
0.454, 0.525, 0.600, 0.940, and 1.019 micrometers.  The 0.940 um channel
allows concentration profiles of water vapor to be mapped.  The 0.448 um
channel provides an additional channel for nitrogen dioxide detection, and
the 0.525 um channel is an additional channel used for aerosol detection.
The 0.600 um channel, which is near the center of the Chappuis ozone band,
is the primary channel used for ozone measurement.  The remaining channels 
allow for the separation of atmospheric extinction along the line-of-sight
that are due to Rayleigh scattering, aerosols, and nitrogen dioxide.  The
SAGE I and SAGE II channels provide corrections for overlapping
contributions of aerosols and nitrogen dioxide.     

4.4  Instrument Measurement Geometry.  The SAGE I and SAGE II instruments
use the sun as a constant radiant energy source.  The instrument's sensors
measure the radiation that has passed through the Earth's atmosphere
during sunrise and sunset.  The photometers receive a vertically scanned
solar image with respect to the Earth's surface.

The SAGE I photometric data are sampled at a rate of 64 samples per second
per channel and digitized to 12-bit resolution.  Accuracy of the sample is
1 bit.  Sampling occurs twice per orbit for durations varying from 3 to
10 minutes each, depending on the angle between the orbital plane of the
spacecraft and the Earth-Sun vector.  The SAGE I field-of-view,
approximately 0.5 arc-minutes, produces an approximate vertical resolution
of 1 km at altitudes ranging from 10 km to the horizon.

The nominal scan rate of the SAGE II instrument is 15 arc-minutes per
second.  The radiometric data are sampled at a rate of 64 samples per
second per channel and digitized to 12-bit accuracy.  Sampling occurs 
twice per orbit for durations varying from 3 to 10 minutes each.  The 
SAGE II vertical resolution is approximately 1 km at altitudes ranging
from cloud tops to 10 km.

                                                                                
5.  DATA PROCESSING SEQUENCE                                                    
                                                                                
5.1  Processing Steps and Data Sets.  The SAGE I and II series raw data
are merged with their associated ephemeris and meteorological data sets
to form file sets that contain the information to process the experiment 
data into the ozone profiles described in this document.  The temperature 
profiles in the meteorological data are provided by the NOAA National 
Meteorological Center (NMC).  Platform ephemeris data for the experiments 
are extrapolated from definitive data into weekly data sets by GSFC.            
                                                                                
From these data sets NASA Langley Research Center (LaRC) personnel 
calculate ozone number density and volume mixing ratio as a function of
altitude and store them on SAGE I and II Profile Tapes. 
                                                                                
5.2  Derivation Techniques/Algorithms.  Data from each satellite sunrise 
and sunset event are converted to an atmospheric transmission versus 
tangent-height profile.  The mean slant path optical depth is calculated 
for 1 km altitude bins using the Lambert-Beer law.  The following 
three-step inversion is then performed:                                 
                                                                                
     1.  The effects of Rayleigh scattering are calculated from the             
         meteorological data and subtracted out                                
                                                                                
     2.  The slant path optical depths are separated by species:
         aerosols, ozone, nitrogen dioxide, or water vapor 
                                                                                
     3.  Inversion from slant path optical depth to vertical extinction
         is performed using the Twomey modification of the Chahine 
         nonlinear inversion.                                  
                                                                                
5.3  Special Corrections/Adjustments.  During the processing of SAGE I and 
SAGE II data, corrections are made for solar limb darkening, atmospheric
refraction, and Rayleigh scattering to derive the parameter data sets. 
When atmospheric temperature and pressure profiles are not available to
make these corrections, latitude-dependent model temperature/pressure
profiles, based on standard atmospheric profiles, are provided.  If model
data are provided, the event containing model data is so annotated.          
                                                                                
5.4  Processing Changes.  As a result of published corrections to the
NOAA temperature data at 5 mb and above and, the desire to compare SAGE I
and SAGE II data for long-term trend studies, the SAGE I data were 
reprocessed using improved retrieval techniques employed for SAGE II in
1991.      
                                                                                
                                                                                
6.  QUALITY ASSESSMENT                                                          
                                                                                
6.1  Data Validation by Producer.  SAGE I and SAGE II results have              
been validated by comparison with those obtained from a wide range of           
sensors, including an airborne LIDAR, balloon-borne optical particle            
counters, impactors, spectrometer strobes, ozonesondes, ozone  
rocketsondes, and other satellite data sets.  Details are contained in
the references in Item 11.                                     
                                                                                
NASA has made facilities available at LaRC so that visiting scientists 
may analyze and evaluate SAGE I and SAGE II data sets with their 
correlative data.  Predictions of SAGE II overpasses for correlative 
purposes are also available upon request from LaRC.                      
                                                                                
6.2  Confidence Level/Accuracy Judgment.  Because measurement accuracy is
a function of altitude, each atmospheric profile array is accompanied by 
an error array.  Typically, ozone concentration uncertainties are less
than 10 percent from cloud tops to 60 km.                         
                                                                                
6.3  Usage Guidance.  Numerous studies using SAGE I and SAGE II data have       
been conducted.  SAGE I and SAGE II results have been combined to study    
long-term trends in stratospheric ozone.                                        
                                                                                
                                                                                
